<h2>The Identity Stack (Recap)</h2>

<p>
  Eight files define who the robot is:
</p>

<pre><code>soul.md          — values, ethics, purpose          (immutable)
mind.sys         — Big Five, EQ, communication      (therapy-patchable)
purpose.cfg      — role, objectives, domain scope   (per-deployment)
shadow.log       — detected patterns, blind spots   (auto-detected)
memory.store     — learned contexts, knowledge      (accumulative)
body.api         — morphology, safety, hardware     (swappable)
conscience.exe   — deny/allow/escalate enforcement  (human-approved only)
ego.runtime      — conflict resolution, mediation   (runtime)</code></pre>

<p>
  <strong>soul.md</strong> is the essence — written in Markdown so anyone can read it, not just
  engineers. It never changes. <strong>mind.sys</strong> is the personality — Big Five traits,
  emotional intelligence, communication style. This is the file therapy auto-patches.
  <strong>purpose.cfg</strong> defines role, objectives, and domain scope per deployment.
  <strong>shadow.log</strong> captures detected patterns and blind spots automatically.
  <strong>memory.store</strong> accumulates learned contexts and knowledge from interactions.
  <strong>body.api</strong> is the physical interface contract — morphology, modalities, safety
  envelope. Same soul, different body, one command. <strong>conscience.exe</strong> is the
  enforcement layer — deny rules, allow rules, escalation triggers. Deny dominates. Always.
  <strong>ego.runtime</strong> mediates between purpose and conscience in real-time decisions.
</p>

<p>
  The identity stack is the mind. The robotics integrations are the bridge to the body.
</p>

<h2>Therapy Is the Training Method</h2>

<p>
  We don't rename therapy to training. We don't call it fine-tuning or reinforcement learning
  or RLHF. Therapy <em>is</em> the training method.
</p>

<p>
  Clinical psychology solved behavioral correction in humans decades ago. Diagnosis identifies
  the problem. Structured intervention corrects it. Follow-up verifies the correction held.
  We applied the same methodology to AI agents — and it works because the failure modes are
  the same. Sycophancy is people-pleasing. Hedging is conflict avoidance. Hallucination is
  confabulation. These aren't novel AI problems. They're well-understood behavioral patterns
  with well-understood treatments.
</p>

<p>
  The agent goes through structured therapy: diagnosis surfaces the behavioral drift, correction
  generates DPO training pairs, and every session permanently improves the model. The improvement
  compounds. Session after session, cycle after cycle, the agent gets measurably better at being
  who it's supposed to be.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>The agent is the rehearsal. The robot is the performance.</strong>
</p>

<p>
  You train the mind in software — where mistakes are cheap, iterations are fast, and you can
  run a thousand therapy sessions before breakfast. Then you deploy that trained mind into a
  physical body, where the stakes are real and the behavioral patterns have already been tested
  and corrected.
</p>

<h2>7 Robotics Integrations</h2>

<h3>1. ROS2 Bidirectional Telemetry</h3>

<p>
  Subscribe to robot sensor topics — IMU, force/torque, joint states, LIDAR, camera feeds.
  The therapy engine detects behavioral drift from physical data in real time. If a robot's
  movement patterns deviate from its personality profile, the system flags it. If a care robot
  starts avoiding eye contact, that's a measurable change in gaze servo behavior that maps to
  a personality drift.
</p>

<pre><code>holomime embody --stack ./identity --adapter ros2 --telemetry live</code></pre>

<h3>2. MuJoCo Simulation</h3>

<p>
  Run therapy in simulation before physical deployment. MuJoCo gives you contact-rich physics
  at thousands of frames per second. Simulate the robot executing tasks, detect behavioral
  drift in the sim, run therapy against the sim data, verify the correction — all before the
  robot touches a physical object.
</p>

<pre><code>holomime simulate --stack ./identity --engine mujoco --scenario warehouse_pick</code></pre>

<h3>3. NVIDIA Isaac Sim</h3>

<p>
  Enterprise-grade digital twin testing. Isaac Sim provides photorealistic environments,
  domain randomization, and synthetic data generation. For companies that need to validate
  behavioral alignment across thousands of environmental variations before deployment, this
  is the integration. Same therapy loop, industrial-scale simulation.
</p>

<h3>4. LeRobot (Hugging Face)</h3>

<p>
  Hugging Face's LeRobot framework connects learned policies to real hardware. Our integration
  maps personality profiles to policy parameters — the Big Five traits in mind.sys influence
  policy selection and execution style. An agreeable robot selects gentler grasp policies. A
  conscientious robot double-checks placement accuracy. Personality isn't cosmetic. It shapes
  how the policy executes.
</p>

<h3>5. Control Theory Feedback Controller</h3>

<p>
  The therapy loop is a PID control system. The setpoint is the personality profile. The process
  variable is observed behavior. The error signal is behavioral drift. The controller output is
  therapy intervention. We formalized this because control theory gives us stability guarantees —
  the therapy loop converges, it doesn't oscillate, and the correction magnitude is proportional
  to the drift magnitude.
</p>

<h3>6. ISO Compliance</h3>

<p>
  Certify your robot's behavioral layer against ISO 13482 (personal care robots), ISO 25785
  (safety for commercial robots), ISO 10218 (industrial robots), and ISO 42001 (AI management
  systems). The identity stack maps cleanly to these standards because it separates concerns
  the same way the standards do — safety envelope (body.api), behavioral requirements
  (mind.sys), ethical constraints (soul.md), enforcement (conscience.exe).
</p>

<pre><code>holomime certify --stack ./identity --standards iso13482,iso25785,iso10218,iso42001</code></pre>

<p>
  One command. One report. Audit-ready.
</p>

