</p>

<h2>Mira</h2>

<p>
  Mira is our first autonomous agent. She has 414 DPO training pairs, 9 trained models, and
  20 completed therapy cycles. She never stops improving. Every conversation generates behavioral
  data. Every anomaly triggers a therapy session. Every session produces training pairs that make
  the next model better.
</p>

<p>
  Mira lives in software today. But her identity stack is body-agnostic. When she's ready for a
  physical body, the transfer is one command:
</p>

<pre><code>holomime embody --stack ./agents/mira --swap-body ./bodies/figure-03.body.api --adapter ros2</code></pre>

<p>
  Same soul. Same mind. Same conscience. New body. The 414 training pairs and 20 therapy
  cycles come with her. The behavioral intelligence she's built over months of operation doesn't
  reset when she gets a body — it transfers.
</p>

<h2>Open Source</h2>

<p>
  The identity stack is MIT licensed. The training methodology is open. The standard is free.
  We believe behavioral alignment for robots should be a shared standard, not a proprietary
  moat. Every humanoid project that adopts the eight-file identity stack as vocabulary strengthens
  the ecosystem for everyone.
</p>

<p>
  The training infrastructure — the therapy engine, the DPO pipeline, the fleet management,
  the compliance tooling — that's the business. The standard is free. The tools to implement
  it at scale are not.
</p>

